And look at how FIFA's COVID-19 Relief Fund has supported football in the US Virgin Islands 🇻🇮.

“Il pallone d’oro 2013? La più grande ingiustizia della mia carriera.  E non solo per me, ma per molte altre persone. Sono stato il migliore quell’anno e ho finito terzo, non avevo nulla da invidiare a Messi e Ronaldo, lo dico con tutta l’umiltà possibile perché è la verità”  Non sempre la vita va come dovrebbe andare, non sempre puoi dire di aver avuto ciò che meritavi e di certo non sempre le cose che ti accadono sono qualcosa che potevi evitare o da cui proteggerti. Lui lo sa bene, benissimo, lo ha imparato già a due anni, quando in un incidente stradale, finì fuori dall’abitacolo. I suoi non si fecero nulla, lui invece nessuno sapeva se sarebbe sopravvissuto con quei tagli sul viso. Alla fine ce la fece, ma per tutti, da quel giorno, lui fu Scarface™.  Crescere con quelle cicatrici a guardarti ogni mattina non fu facile, ma Franck Ribéry, nonostante bulli, solitudine, tristezza e insicurezza, alla fine trovò la sua posizione, il suo ruolo in questo mondo. Ed era dentro un campo di pallone.  Dalla periferia più povera di Boulogne-Sur-Mer, Nord-Pas-De-Calais, France Normandia, lì dove gli alleati cambiarono le sorti del conflitto nell’estate del 1944, lui riuscì a cambiare il suo destino, che pareva quello del classico sotto-proletario disperato, di uno condannato a fare lavori pesanti e mal-pagati tutta la vita. Calce e mattoni furono i suoi compagni preferiti, prima di riuscire a farsi spazio nel calcio, ma chissà se pensava di diventare chi è diventato Franck. Di certo svegliarsi alle 5, caffè e via a tirare su muri, gli ha insegnato cosa conta e cosa no nella vita, non è stato un santi intendiamoci, è finito dentro un paio di scandali a luci rosse ma roba di poco conto, nulla di malvagio o di imperdonabile. Non almeno se si pensa cosa abbia voluto dire per lui, per tutta la vita, guardare una ragazza e sapere che 99 su 100 avrebbe distolto lo sguardo. A 6 anni piuttosto dello specchio guardava il pallone, a 13 già era nella LOSC ma era turbolento, pieno di rabbia, a scuola non andava per nulla bene, reagiva ad ogni provocazione. Ufficialmente fu fatto fuori perché “era troppo piccolo”, ma la realtà è che andava per conto suo in campo e fuori.  Ritornò a casa, entrò nelle file del USBCo - Union Sportive Boulogne Côte d'Opale Infos ci restò per due stagioni, prima di essere notato da OAC - Olympique d'Alès en Cévennes, poi al Stade Brestois 29, tutte squadre delle serie minori. In fin dei conti, era già tanto, pensavano in molti.  Non lui. Non segna tanto, ma in campo corre come un matto, fa impazzire le difese, è un’ala che all’occorrenza sa fare anche la mezza punta e il trequartista, sia a destra che a sinistra. Ha un controllo della palla incredibile, dribbla e salta l’uomo ogni volta che può, ha una grande visione di gioco, fantasia, spirito combattivo, sa attaccare lo spazio molto bene, crossa benissimo. Se ne accorge il FC Metz che finalmente lo porta a coronare il suo sogno: esordire in Ligue 1 Uber Eats.  Cominciano a paragonarlo a Robert Pires, attira l’attenzione di tanti club e squadre, è giovane, ha voglia di fare, è di una ragazza che va in estinzione, quella dei giocatori che creano superiorità numerica, tuttofare offensivi che danno del tu al pallone. Finisce al Galatasaray alla corte di Gheorghe Hagi, il Maradona dei Carpazi, un altro spirito ribelle e caotico come era lui.  In Turchia diventa idolo dei tifosi, lo soprannominano "Ferraribery", scopre l’Islam, ci si converte, per la prima volta forse si sente parte di qualcosa. Ma in Turchia le cose si guastano. Non lo pagano come hanno stabilito, cercano di costringerlo a firmare documenti che attestano il falso,il suo manager e il Direttore sportivo lo minacciano fisicamente. Fa ricorso alla FIFA, se ne torna a casa, se ne torna al Olympique de Marseille. Lì ha finalmente il 7 sulla schiena, per due stagioni aiuti la città meticcia di Francia, a rifarsi un nome in casa e in UEFA Europa League.  Nello stesso anno, il 2006, esordisce con la maglia della Équipe de France de Football, nel Mondiale tedesco si fa notare come il giovane più promettente del torneo, gioca in tutti i match o quasi, segna contro la Selección Española de Fútbol (SeFutbol).  Ma in finale, anche se ha un paio di palloni buoni, non riesce a superare Fabio Cannavaro e Gianluigi Buffon.  Dalla panchina, vede la Nazionale Italiana di Calcio avviarsi verso la quarta coppa sulla corsa di Fabio Grosso. Sarà la prima di una serie di delusioni cocenti con i Blues.  L’anno dopo, si fanno sotto una marea di club per averlo. Ma alla fine, tra Premier League e Lega Serie A e LaLiga, Franck opta per la Bundesliga per il FC Bayern München. E con loro, diventa il giocatore che è nato per essere, il motorino sempre accesso della trequarti, davanti ci sta pure Luca Toni a fare da ariete, ma è assieme allo spilungone anarchico Orange Arjen Robben che forma un duo laterale da sogno, roba da calcio anni 90, con lui che esibisce quel sorriso con quelle cicatrici, pare quasi essere la versione pallonara del Joker, non fosse altro per imprevedibilità, fantasia, per l’incredibile capacità di divertirsi anche nell’Olimpo del calcio.  Il tutto a dispetto di infortuni, momenti storti, di pressioni mediatiche e non, di annate storte e di trionfi. Con la maglia dei bavaresi, #Ribery diventa il simbolo del calcio francese, l’erede dei grandi di Francia…ma lì, tra i dominatori di Germania, trova anche la sua dimensione personale, smette di sentirsi un naufrago, eternamente messo in discussione. 12 anni, 273 presenza, 86 gol, ben 9 scudetti, 6 Coppe di Germania, 1 Coppa di Lega, 5 SuperCoppe. Nel 2013 è il grande protagonista della cavalcata trionfale in UEFA Champions League fa una stagione semplicemente pazzesca, per tutti dovrebbe essere lui il pallone d’oro. Invece va a Cristiano Ronaldo, Leo Messi è secondo, lui solo terzo.  Una delle tante assegnazioni dubbie di questi dieci anni dominati dai due fenomeni che però quell’anno gli stavano tranquillamente dietro.   Tante vittorie si, ma quelle più di prestigio gli sfuggono In Nazionale ad Euro 2008 si fa male contro di noi, nella partita decisiva. Nel 2010, la squadra è un’accozzaglia di gente senza arte né parte, divi da banlieu, fighetti pigri. Gioca male anche perché è nello scandalo a base di escort minorenni che di lì a poco quasi lo fa cadere in rovina. Verrà poi assolto per non aver saputo di essere finito con una 16enne. Fa bene agli Europei del 2012 ma si esce ai quarti, con l’Armada di Spagna. Il 2014 potrebbe essere l’ultima chance, ma l’ennesimo infortunio lo taglia fuori.  Col Bayern a partire dal 2017 sente che ormai siamo ai titoli di coda, se ne va nel 2019, è stato la bandiera del club, ha fatto qualcosa che resterà. Decide di venire da noi, si mette in gioco nella ACF Fiorentina.  Il fisico spesso cede, ma quando sta bene regala emozioni, dribbling, impegno, è sempre il ragazzino che correva dietro al pallone perché non aveva altro. Per ora non ha però soddisfatto le attese, ha 38 anni, il fisico ormai non è più quello dei tempi d’oro. Si parla di un ritiro a fine campionato.  Ma anche fosse, è stato meraviglioso lo stesso, vedere lui, uno degli ultimi dribblatori, uno degli ultimi artisti del pallone, parzialmente incompiuto come capita ai grandi pittori, indecifrabile come i jazzisti, riscattarsi da un destino di paria della vita, diventare icona, idolo, andare oltre ciò che vedeva allo specchio.  Tanti Auguri Scarface. L’ultimo folletto di Francia.

Após a Data FIFA para a realização das European Qualifiers para a FIFA World Cup 2022 🇶🇦, as ligas nacionais de clubes voltaram com tudo nesse final de semana na Europa! Na Ligue 1 Uber Eats 🇫🇷, o LOSC reassumiu a liderança da competição, ao vencer em um confronto direto o ex-líder PSG - Paris Saint-Germain; Na Lega Serie A 🇮🇹, o "Derby della Mole" terminou empatado sendo esse um resultado ruim para ambos, já que a Juventus não apenas vê as chances de título se reduzirem cada vez mais, como também corre grandes riscos de não se classificar para a próxima UEFA Champions League 🇪🇺, enquanto que o Torino Football Club ainda segue próximo da temida Zona de Rebaixamento para a Lega B 🇮🇹; Na Bundesliga 🇩🇪, o FC Bayern München se aproximou ainda mais da conquista, ao vencer o vice-líder RB Leipzig e abrindo distância na ponta da tabela; Na Premier League 🏴󠁧󠁢󠁥󠁮󠁧󠁿, o Manchester City às vésperas de conquistar o título, praticamente encerrou o sonho do Leicester City Football Club de conquistar a taça com uma imponente vitória, enquanto que o Liverpool FC venceu o Arsenal e segue na briga por vaga na próxima UEFA Champions League 🇪🇺; Já na Espanha, dois jogos chamaram a atenção, em LaLiga 🇪🇸 o Sevilla FC venceu o Atlético de Madrid, colocando em risco a liderança dos "Colchoneros", enquanto que na "Grande Final" da Copa do Rei da Espanha 👑🇪🇸 válida ainda pela temporada 2019/2020 (já que os clubes bascos desejavam uma decisão com torcida presente, coisa que infelizmente não pôde acontecer em razão da permanência da pandemia de Covid-19), a Real Sociedad de Fútbol conquistou a taça pela terceira vez (1909, 1986/1987 e 2019/2020) ao vencer o Athletic Club. ⚽️

To all these footballers, I am proud of your commitment to fighting for what is right and I encourage others to add their voices to this important message in the coming days” said FIFA Secretary-General, Fatma Samoura. Between 22-28 November, five #FIFA staff are living and working @kick4life in #Lesotho, as part of the inaugural Employee Volunteer Program.  Kick4Life FC is the world’s first football club exclusively dedicated to social change. As a charity and a social enterprise, their mission is to transform the lives of vulnerable young people in Lesotho, promoting long-term sustainable development.  In more recent years, two major social enterprises were opened at the Kick4Life Centre. A restaurant, and K4L Hotel & Conference Centre. The enterprises generate income for the delivery of the charity's programmes as well as providing structured training and employment opportunities for young people.  We'll share more clips in the coming days, shining a spotlight on the experience of our #volunteers.

FIFA legend Yaya Touré was in the Maldives today, to see the impact of FIFA Forward projects.  The Hulhumale Football School project is a four-storied building where 100 of the best footballers from the country will be accommodated and trained. The facility will also have two artificial pitches and is expected to be ready by February 2020. The whole project is funded by the Government.   Afterwards he visited the Maafannu Sports Arena Social Project, which will see a FIFA contribution of $1.75m. A three storied building will be constructed, containing office space, classrooms, dormitory space and dressing rooms for teams and referees. Plus a gymnasium, medical room and food court. A full size artificial turf will also be in place. The project will be ready in May 2020. Once ready, the facility will be used for training of first division club teams, youth development teams and for grassroots football. It will also become the Home of Football Association of Maldives.

The FIFA President and Deputy General Secretary Zvonimir Boban telephoned coach Ezio Maiuri of Italian Serie D team Portici. Why? After his team had scored a goal while an opponent was injured, he asked his players to let the other team score. A fantastic Fair Play gesture, that they read about in the Italian media, and wanted to personally acknowledge. Bravo!  Un gran gesto di fair play da parte di Mister Ezio Maiuri, a suo tempo allenatore del Portici, squadra che milita in Serie D. Maiuri durante la sfida casalinga con la Nocerina ha imposto ai suoi calciatori di far pareggiare gli ospiti dopo che la squadra era passata in vantaggio con un avversario a terra infortunato. Tanto di cappello Mister Maiuri. Il Calcio ha bisogno di molti altri comportamenti e gesti esemplari come il suo.

A group of 27 Djiboutian football referees have been trained at a FIFA-level course in their country's capital Djibouti.  The training course was organised by the Djiboutian Football Federation in collaboration with FIFA from 23 to 27 September 2017.  FIFA instructors Noumandiez Doué (Côte d'Ivoire) and Mohamed Houssein Ali (Djibouti) were assisted by local instructors Aden Robleh Rayaleh and Abdo Ali Mohamed.  All 27 participants passed both fitness and theory tests taken during the five-day course.

At the end of last month, John McKellar was one of 50 fans who attended a Fan Forum at FIFA HQ. John organises a new form of football, growing in popularity for elderly men and women, called Walking Football. And John told us about Alan.  Alan has suffered from severe depression for several years, mainly down to the suicide of his brother. This had a profound effect on Alan and he was unable to leave his house for over four years.  He first got into Walking Football after being persuaded by his wife to join in. Eventually he plucked up the courage and came along.  The first few months for him were extremely difficult. Alan found it very hard to talk to anyone, but very slowly, he started to come out of his shell.  Alan is still prone to bouts of depression and anxiety, but at BayCity Strollers Walking Football at BayPoint Sandwich (brilliant name!), he has lots of support. He was recently recognised at the local Thanet Sports Awards for his courage.  We want to congratulate John and Alan. You're never too old to play football, even at walking pace. Amazing work. Beautiful story. ⚽️❤️👏👏👏👏👏👏 #inspiration #love #football

“The reality of football is quite different for men and women, and it is something we need to work urgently together to change. There must be a common view of the path we should take, and I’m glad to help in shaping that view.”  Sun Wen is the best female footballer China has produced. She played at four FIFA Women's World Cups and two Olympic tournaments. Top scorer and best player in 1999, she was voted joint best player of the last century, alongside American Michelle Akers. Now, she is supporting the Chinese FA overhaul their grassroots girl's and women's football strategy alongside FIFA.

On 15 April 1989, an FA Cup semi final was held at Hillsborough in Sheffield, between Liverpool and Nottingham Forest.  That day is etched into the memories of many football fans around the world, after 96 Liverpool fans died in a crush on the terraces. More than 750 fans were also injured.  For 27 years, families of those who died have relentlessly campaigned, after it was initially concluded that fans were to blame. Today, after a long inquest, it was finally concluded those fans were NOT to blame.  Emerging outside the court, families of the deceased spontaneously broke out into the club anthem, ‘You’ll Never Walk Alone.’ Today, one of the most significant hashtags on Social Media has been validated after all these years. #JFT96  @liverpoolfc #LFC #YNWA

FIFA President Gianni Infantino arrived in Addis-Ababa last night, where he met with a delegation of the Ethiopian FA led by President Juneidi Tilmo.  Football development was the main topic on the agenda. This morning, the FIFA President had the opportunity to visit the headquarters of the Association, a FIFA Goal project, as well as the Ethiopian Youth Sports Academy, a technical centre for young female and male players. Before departing the country, he had meetings with Ethiopia's Sports Minister Redwan Hussein and Foreign Affairs Minister Tedros Adhanom.  The FIFA delegation then went to the neighbouring country of Djibouti, where the programme included a meeting with Prime Minister Abdoulkader Kamil Mohamed and a visit of the Djibouti FA Headquarters – another FIFA Goal project. President Infantino then attended his second 2017 CAN qualifiers game in as many days, with Liberia defeating hosts Djibouti 1-0.  The FIFA President will conclude his three-day trip to Africa on Friday with a visit to Gabon, hosts of the next edition of the CAF African Cup of Nations which will be played in 2017.

On his 46th birthday, Gianni Infantino made his first visit as FIFA President to a Member Association. His debut destination was South Sudan, FIFA's newest Member Association.  After meeting the Head of State, President Salva Kiir Mayardit, he inaugurated the new South Sudan FA headquarters with the President of country’s FA Chabour Goc. The inauguration was particularly poignant as the building was constructed thanks to the FIFA Goal Programme.  Later in the day, the FIFA President attended the CAF Africa Cup of Nations qualifier between South Sudan and Benin, which the visitors won 2-1.

FIFA is pressing ahead with its initiative to build a global club licensing system, with the latest seminar on the topic currently under way in Johannesburg, South Africa.  Organised in conjunction with the Confederation of African Football (CAF), the two-day seminar has brought together 13 member associations from across southern Africa to share information, expertise and experiences about the FIFA club licensing system. The system aims to improve club football by setting minimum standards in key areas such as stadium safety, fan experience and youth football development. Clubs then need to meet these standards to qualify for certain international competitions.  Photo: Michel Papemsi, Pamics Star Media

#OnThisDay in 1921, Jules Rimet became FIFA's third President and remains the longest-serving one, holding the office for 33 years. One of his most significant contributions was the establishment of the FIFA World Cup, which he proposed in 1928 and was first played in 1930. The World Cup trophy was renamed in his honor in 1946. In 1956, two years after his retirement, Rimet passed away, just two days after his 83rd birthday. #RIP #JulesRimet #FIFAPresident #FIFA #WorldCup #history #FIFAMuseum #trophy

Ernest Mtawali learned how to play by juggling the football up the hill on the way to his home from school in Chilomoni. He debuted at the age of 18 with the Malawi national team - of which now, at 51, he is the coach. He played under Alain Giresse in Toulouse and had trials alongside Irish great Roy Keane at Nottingham Forest. He featured for Talleres and Newell’s Old Boys in Argentina. He could have been better than Diego Maradona had he only had the right support as a kid (or so he says, with a smile). He is happy that kids in Malawi are now receiving that support.  Photo: Simon Bruty

“If I had had an opportunity like this, I would’ve landed myself in the English Premier League,” James Sangala, 30, says with a huge smile, but only half-jokingly. Maybe not even half.  “My generation had the talent and the hunger, but didn’t have the means. I’m talking about the basics – equipment. Even the top-flight teams in Malawi struggle to acquire boots and footballs. So, when I was introduced to the project of an under-15 league I knew exactly how huge this was: each team gets 25 footballs, there’s organised coaching… I started playing seriously at that age and, with none of this support, I played in Angola and South Africa. I spent nine years with the national team, and in 2010 we qualified for the African Cup of Nations for the first time in 35 years.”   James is no longer a professional footballer, although he still plays; just about every day. As the manager of youth football at the Football Association of Malawi, he keeps on living his same dreams, only now through the younger generations – and with a new injection of support and hope. “Honestly, people have no clue of what football means in a country like this and what kind of talent is wasted.”   As he speaks, James is pointing to a group of dozens of kids enjoying sandwiches and soft drinks, following the first organised league game of their lives. “Malawi should be qualifying for the AFCON time and again and, eventually, the World Cup. But we need to take care of our foundation.”  Photo: Simon Bruty
Kids under 15 years old from across Malawi are having the chance to play organised, competitive football for the first time in their lives. It will now be the first of many.

31st October, 2015. The day when the under-15 youth football league kicked-off in Blantyre, Malawi, was the first time Humphrey got the chance to play football wearing a proper team kit. “It’s nice. You even feel like looking at yourself,” he says, innocently admiring his own shirt and captain’s armband. “Maybe it’s just my impression, but I think I play better wearing the kit.”  Photo: Simon Bruty

When Humphrey was six years old, he watched football on the TV and made up his mind for good: he wanted to be a professional player, and to play for the Malawian national team. He spent the early years of his life working towards just that - playing football whenever he could. But he never had the chance to do so for a team coached by a trained instructor in a fully-organised league… until now. “It’s different. There’s pressure. You may even get better all by yourself, but you never learn how to play in a group.”  Photo: Simon Bruty

Brazil won the Copa Sudamerica Feminina, Russia will defend their FIFA Beach Soccer World Cup title, and FIFA's grassroots courses continued around the globe.
August saw Germany win the U20 FIFA Women's World Cup, Miroslav Klose & Howard Webb retire, and the world say goodbye to a much-loved actor and comedian.
July was the month of the FIFA World Cup Final. But also the month we lost one of the greatest players, never to have played at a World Cup: Alfredo di Stefano.

Champions League winners were confirmed, provisional World Cup squads announced, and football lost another member of its family, as the world mourned Tito Vilanova.
